{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656805"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:18:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:18:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18766"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18766","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18766"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.45,0.07,0.12,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11498"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77413"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11498"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18766"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62920"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4905"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5373"},{"type":"tags","id":"9888"},{"type":"tags","id":"9935"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26610"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26614"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77413"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA healthy 25-year-old woman begins exercising on a cycle ergometer. Her breathing rate and depth increase immediately as she starts pedaling.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary stimulus for the initial increase in ventilation during exercise?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased arterial oxygen saturation","Neural signals from central motor command","Increased blood lactate concentration","Decreased blood pH","Increased arterial carbon dioxide tension"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eneural signals from central motor command\u003C/strong\u003E provide the primary stimulus for the immediate increase in ventilation at exercise onset. This feed-forward mechanism anticipates metabolic needs before chemical changes occur in the blood.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased arterial oxygen saturation\u003C/strong\u003E - Oxygen saturation typically remains stable during moderate exercise\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased blood lactate concentration\u003C/strong\u003E - Lactate does not increase significantly during early or moderate exercise\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased blood pH\u003C/strong\u003E - pH changes occur too slowly to account for immediate ventilatory responses\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased arterial carbon dioxide tension\u003C/strong\u003E - CO2 changes lag behind the initial ventilatory response\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EWhile chemical factors become important as exercise continues, the initial rapid increase in ventilation is primarily driven by central command and feedback from muscle and joint mechanoreceptors. This ensures ventilation increases appropriately even before metabolic changes occur in the blood.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["During exercise, central command from motor centers provides anticipatory increases in ventilation.","Mechanoreceptors in muscles and joints provide feedback to increase ventilation during exercise.","Chemical changes in blood (CO2, H+) provide additional respiratory drive during exercise."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62920"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18766"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62920"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T22:21:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T22:21:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11498"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77413"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type